caption: The atmosphere at this restaurant was fabulous, we sat on the gallery which was a beautiful view. Service: We ate on the balcony, the servers were confused as to which tables were theirs; our server spilled water all over my son then (accidentally) hit him in the face with the plates when trying to clear the table (but like how does that happen?), and then walked around for 5 minutes with our card forgetting to run it so we could cash out. Atmosphere: you can hear bands playing nearby which is cool, but keep in mind if you want to have conversation you won't be able to if you're on the balcony, also the balcony is tilted downwards, towards the street which is kind of weird for your positioning as you end up sitting sideways... which I mean, isn't the worst but like its awkward. But, there is seating inside both downstairs and upstairs. The restrooms upstairs (I'm not sure if there were any downstairs) are very interesting- I don't think there is air flow in them, and only allow for one person at a time. Lastly, I'm starting to wonder if this is an issue in a lot of the buildings, but while in the staircase all you can smell is the overwhelming wafting of natural gas.

This photo represents a mixed drink called a mimosa at the  Cornet Restaurant on Bourbon Street in New Orleans Louisiana. I've been to 15 different restaurants and ordered the same drink and usually  in a glass what about 16 oz of liquid not including ice. Upon my initial complaint to the manager, he then he explained since we are on the upper deck they cannot we serve this drink in a glass container which is why the cup is plastic. Totally missing the point, I made it known to the manager that the drink was received in a plastic cup that was half empty, literally. The manager then look at me with a straight face and asked me whether or not I would like a smaller cup.  Knowing that this man was looking at me insulting my intelligence he kept the conversation more focus on the fact that the drink had to be served in a plastic cup rather than glass telling me that it would look different if you served it to me and a regular Fountain glass and only appearing to be a small portion in a plastic cup. I would strongly suggest if you want more bang for your buck and ordering a drink with your meal, do not bother coming to this restaurant because not only do they rip you off they insult your intelligence and belittle you.

Being at New Orleans for our first visit and first meal, we could not have picked a better place. We asked to sit on the upper balcony and ate our authentic cuisine while watching the crazy people on Bourbon St. The food was delicious, and very reasonably priced. I got Red Beans and Rice for $16 and got a delicious, generous portion with cornbread to die for. My husband got "Taste of New Orleans" for $18 and it consisted of real jambalaya, gumbo and cachon de lait....It was the perfect meal and our waitress, Maiya, was outstanding. Telling us about the food and the area. She was truly a beautiful person, on the inside and out. We definitely will stop there next time we visit NO. Side note....the next day we went to get a beignet at the famous Cafe Du Monde, and decided to sit by the water on the riverwalk area on a perfect weather day. We sat on a bench and realized we could see Maiya (our waitress from Cornet) sitting a ways down, probably waiting to start work. She didn't know we could see her. A local lady was selling beer and waters out of a rolling cooler and walked past Maiya, Even though Maiya was going to work in a bit, she called them woman over to buy a water and help her out with a sale,,,and then Maiya asked the man who had been sitting by himself, a bench away from her, if he wanted a water or a beer. It was apparent the man was down on his luck and her random act of kindness was amazing. He accepted her offer, and got a beer. Maiya paid for it, put her headphones back in and they went back into their separate worlds. We will never forget witnessing her kindness. The world would be a better place with more people like her.

Terrible service!!! Very slow!

Overpriced tiny servings; food was cold; waited forever to even order drinks from our table; bathrooms were a mess.

Food was ok, Service was not great, long wait for food.
Average food, good view of Bourbon street

The alligator sausage was awesome. The view was great.  Clearly saw the parades and able to get pictures. This was early and when I came by later I was still impressed what front a  row seat to the action the balcony seating at the Corner provided.
Good drinks and upstairs bar.

My wife and I ate there last night. The door man was very friendly and a great attribute to the restaurant. The reason for the 3 star rating is because my wife got a catfish poboy and she really enjoyed it. I unfortunately got their jumbalia and it was cold and a very small portion for 17 dollars.
Very slow service. Waitress was not very friendly. Extremely loud, right outside of Bourbon Street. Not much but bar food, meaning fried.

Fun place to grab a drink. Food was ok, but in no hurry to go back. A little pricey for what your getting. Service was friendly, both front door and bar staff. I would recommend the friend green tomatoes
We had drinks and the shrimp appetizer. You must try the shrimp, it was amazing.

Came in for the second time, the doorman was great! However, the manager was the biggest douchebag on this planet. I'm glad they had drinks, becuase I really wanted to punch this guy.  Also, the food is pretty good.

we were told a half hr for a table. then an hour later, we were told fifteen minutes more. where's the manager ? no one seemed to care that a table of 12 waited THAT LONG for service. AND we bought drinks while waiting. nobody cares. no bueno

Table on the balcony was a great location. You know when you really fancy a salad, but something tells an an experienced traveller that food that had been been boiled or deep fried would be a safer option. Well...it's that kind of place.
Meh.  Wish we had kept walking.

The service was OK but just barely . I had the Catfish it was decent but portion was very small and expensive . I have had starters bigger than than that and it was the main course . I had to leave and get Pizza . I would not go back
Good Food but small portions and extremely expensive.

It was pretty good. The service was good and we were able to sit out on the balcony. The food was a little bland which is why only 4 stars but I would recommend eating here if you're super hungry with their generous portion sizes and to get a good view of Bourbon Street.

Food is not worth the money or the wait. I never had food that was so  Bland. I mean, I even tried putting salt and pepper and that didn't even help and my husband's poboy barely had any shrimp, sad. I would have told the waitress but she got seated a large group so she never came back. When I asked for a manager, she finally came with the bill. I told the manager my complaints and he said that he just got called to work there and straighten things out. However he is not doing a good job because you think after I told him about the bland food , the 6 shrimp on the poboy , no refills or the fact nobody ever came back to checked on us , that he would take something off the bill. Well he did nothing but give us a sad story about coming back to the restaurant to fix all the issues that they have there at that place..Please. The next time I drive an hour to New Orleans to get some food ,  You can bet your money it won't be from this place  Because they are definitely given New Orleans a bad reputation for food. Pricey No flavor food...!

"more than fine actially" in condesending tone. "i dont like being hollered at." is all she offered. another patron at the bar said he had been treated rudely by her too.
Reasonably priced and amazing atmosphere. Very relaxed for being on Bourban street. Great choice of signature cocktails and a food dish for everyone.
Good was great. The Huge Ass Seafood platter had a lot of food.

Stopped in thinking it would be a cool place to eat because of the connection to Armstrong’s cornet. Unfortunately everything about it proved it was a tourist trap with sub par food and service. Ordered tator tots that were obviously microwaved to melt the shredded cheese. Burgers didn’t have much flavor and also had shredded cheese under the burger. No attempt made to even melt it and when the manager came over he claimed that shredded cheese was a southern thing. This was our 3rd burger in New Orleans and the first one with shredded cheese. I gave two stars because the manager comped part of our meal, but left feeling like we had made a bad mistake. Don’t waste a meal here when you can eat at so many other amazing restaurants!
Got seat right away, then waited 30 minutes to order food. Then waited another hour and a half to get the food. Piss poor service.
